# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drug-metabolism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] P450s are, in general, the terminal oxidase enzymes in electron transfer chains, broadly categorized as P450-containing systems.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The term "P450" is derived from the spectrophotometric peak at the wavelength of the absorption maximum of the enzyme (450 nm) when it is in the reduced state and complexed with carbon monoxide.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Most P450s require a protein partner to deliver one or more electrons to reduce the iron (and eventually molecular oxygen).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Genes encoding P450 enzymes, and the enzymes themselves, are designated with the root symbol **CYP** for the superfamily, followed by a number indicating the gene family, a capital letter indicating the subfamily, and another numeral for the individual gene.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The convention is to *italicize* the name when referring to the gene.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] For example, *CYP2E1* is the gene that encodes the enzyme CYP2E1—one of the enzymes involved in paracetamol (acetaminophen) metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The **CYP** nomenclature is the official naming convention, although occasionally **CYP450** or **CYP450** is used synonymously.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] These names should never be used as according to the nomenclature convention (as they denote a P450 in family number 450).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] However, some gene or enzyme names for P450s are also referred to by historical names (e.g.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] P450BM3 for CYP102A1) or functional names, denoting the catalytic activity and the name of the compound used as substrate.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Examples include CYP5A1, thromboxane A2 synthase, abbreviated to TBXAS1 (thromboxane A2 synthase 1), and CYP51A1, lanosterol 14-α-demethylase, sometimes unofficially abbreviated to LDM according to its substrate (lanosterol) and activity (demethylation).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The nomenclature guidelines suggest that members of new CYP families share at least 40% amino-acid identity, while members of subfamilies must share at least 55% amino-acid identity.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Nomenclature committees assign and track both base gene names (Cytochrome P450 Homepage Archived 2010-06-27 at the Wayback Machine) and allele names (CYP Allele Nomenclature Committee).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] These similarity-based groupings are frequently recovered in phylogenetic analyses and members generally share features in their catalytic activities.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Sometimes the suggested similarity thresholds do not exactly match what phylogenetic patterns show (e.g. a new member that is close to a family but only 39% identical), causing what is known as "family creep" as the similarity threshold is reduced, or the occasional split of families.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The taxonomic group blocks are defined for CYP1001–CYP69999 by stretching the taxonomic blocks defined for CYP101–999.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The reservations defined under these groups are not stretched.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] As of April 2026, the most complete database is the P450 Atlas (version 1.3.0) covering 11068 families, 26037 subfamilies, 79577 ortholog groups and 164068 example sequences of ortholog groups.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Comparison between many P450 enzymes of different families give rise to the concept of *clans*, evolutionary grouping of families.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The exact similarity cut-off is poorly defined, but it is generally understood that it should derive from a few first-diverging nodes of a phylogenetic tree.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Some clans only have one family while others are highly diversified with many families within (e.g.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Tracking the emergence of clans and families across many taxonomic groups paints a vivid picture of the evolution of metabolic capabilities.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The active site of cytochrome P450 contains a heme-iron center.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The iron is tethered to the protein via a cysteine thiolate ligand.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] This cysteine and several flanking residues are highly conserved in known P450s, and have the formal PROSITE signature consensus pattern [FW] - [SGNH] - x - [GD] - {F} - [RKHPT] - {P} - C - [LIVMFAP] - [GAD].
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Substrate binding induces electron transfer from NAD(P)H via cytochrome P450 reductase or another associated reductase, converting Fe(III) to Fe(II).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Molecular oxygen binds to the resulting ferrous heme center at the distal axial coordination position, initially giving a dioxygen adduct similar to oxy-myoglobin.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] A second electron is transferred, from either cytochrome P450 reductase, ferredoxins, or cytochrome b5, reducing the Fe-O2 adduct to give a short-lived peroxo state.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The peroxo group formed in step 4 is rapidly protonated twice, releasing one molecule of water and forming the highly reactive species referred to as **P450 Compound 1** (or just Compound I).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] This highly reactive intermediate was isolated in 2010, P450 Compound 1 is an iron(IV) oxo (or ferryl) species with an additional oxidizing equivalent delocalized over the porphyrin and thiolate ligands.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Evidence for the alternative perferryl iron(V)-oxo is lacking.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Depending on the substrate and enzyme involved, P450 enzymes can catalyze any of a wide variety of reactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] A hypothetical hydroxylation is illustrated.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] After the hydroxylated product has been released from the active site, the enzyme returns to its original state, with a water molecule returning to occupy the distal coordination position of the iron nucleus.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] An alternative route for mono-oxygenation is via the "peroxide shunt" (path "S" in figure).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] This pathway entails oxidation of the ferric-substrate complex with oxygen-atom donors such as peroxides and hypochlorites.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] A hypothetical peroxide "XOOH" is shown in the diagram.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Mechanistic details, including the oxygen rebound mechanism, have been investigated with synthetic analogues, consisting of iron oxo heme complexes.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Binding of substrate is reflected in the spectral properties of the enzyme, with an increase in absorbance at 390 nm and a decrease at 420 nm.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] This can be measured by difference spectroscopies and is referred to as the "type I" difference spectrum (see inset graph in figure).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Some substrates cause an opposite change in spectral properties, a "reverse type I" spectrum, by processes that are as yet unclear.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Inhibitors and certain substrates that bind directly to the heme iron give rise to the type II difference spectrum, with a maximum at 430 nm and a minimum at 390 nm (see inset graph in figure).
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] If no reducing equivalents are available, this complex may remain stable, allowing the degree of binding to be determined from absorbance measurements *in vitro* C: If carbon monoxide (CO) binds to reduced P450, the catalytic cycle is interrupted.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] This reaction yields the classic CO difference spectrum with a maximum at 450 nm.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] However, the interruptive and inhibitory effects of CO varies upon different CYPs such that the CYP3A family is relatively less affected.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The heme in cytochrome P450 binds to a conserved sequence: `FxxGxRxCxG`, where "x" denotes some variant amino acid.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The cysteine (C) binds Fe and arginine (R), forming strong electrostatic interactions with negatively charged side chains of the heme.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] The glycine (G) residues within the conserved sequence are essential, as their small structure enables surrounding alpha helices to remain in place without interacting with a variant amino acid.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Many hydroxylation reactions (insertion of hydroxyl groups) use CYP enzymes, but many other hydroxylases exist.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Alpha-ketoglutarate-dependent hydroxylases also rely on an Fe=O intermediate but lack hemes.
[src:drug-metabolism/cytochrome-p450] Methane monooxygenase, which converts methane to methanol, are non-heme iron-and iron-copper-based enzymes.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Many pharmaceutical drugs are lipophilic compounds that readily cross cell membranes and therefore require enzymatic conversion into more hydrophilic metabolites that can be eliminated through urine or bile.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In humans, most drug metabolism occurs in the liver, although the gastrointestinal tract, lungs, kidneys, and other tissues also contribute.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism is commonly described using a three-phase framework: Phase I reactions introduce or expose functional groups, Phase II reactions conjugate drugs or metabolites to endogenous polar molecules, and Phase III processes transport metabolites for excretion.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] These pathways, especially those mediated by the cytochrome P450 enzyme family, are major determinants of drug disposition and phenomena such as the *first pass effect*.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism varies substantially among individuals and is influenced by factors including age, disease, diet, gut microbiota, inherited genetic variation (pharmacogenetics), and exposure to enzyme inducers or inhibitors.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Expression of metabolic enzymes and transporters is further regulated by xenobiotic-sensing receptors such as the pregnane X receptor, constitutive androstane receptor, and aryl hydrocarbon receptor, contributing to changes in clearance and drug interaction profiles.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] These sources of variability influence efficacy, toxicity, therapeutic index, multidrug resistance, and the development of personalized medicine approaches including pharmacogenetic testing.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism may inactivate drugs, generate active metabolites, or bioactivate prodrugs and therefore underlies many clinically important drug and food interactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Integration of metabolic data with pharmacokinetic principles, including hepatic clearance models, physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling, and *in vitro*–*in vivo* extrapolation, supports prediction of systemic exposure and optimization of drug development and clinical dosing.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The field emerged from nineteenth-century studies of chemical biotransformation and became established through the classification of metabolic reactions and the discovery of cytochrome P450 enzymes.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Many pharmaceutical drugs are lipophilic compounds that diffuse across cell membranes and enter cells without requiring specific transport proteins.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] This property is important for drug absorption and distribution, but it also means that organisms cannot completely prevent exposure to membrane-permeable drugs and other foreign compounds.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] As a result, drug metabolism systems evolved to chemically modify and eliminate a wide range of structurally diverse compounds.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Cell membranes act as hydrophobic permeability barriers that restrict the passive diffusion of most hydrophilic molecules.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The uptake of endogenous metabolites and many therapeutic agents is therefore mediated by selective transport systems.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In contrast, many hydrophobic drugs can readily cross biological membranes and therefore require enzymatic conversion into more polar metabolites that can be excreted through urine or bile.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug-metabolizing enzymes consequently display broad substrate specificities and are capable of acting on many chemically unrelated compounds.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In humans, these systems are concentrated primarily in the liver and include enzymes such as the cytochrome P450 oxidases, which catalyse reactions that increase the polarity of drugs and facilitate their elimination.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In addition to metabolizing xenobiotic drugs, cells also contain specialized systems that detoxify reactive by-products generated during normal metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Examples include the glyoxalase system, which removes the reactive aldehyde methylglyoxal, and antioxidant systems that eliminate reactive oxygen species.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism in humans and other animals is commonly described using a three-phase framework derived from the broader principles of xenobiotic metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Phase I reactions introduce or expose functional groups, phase II reactions conjugate drugs or their metabolites to endogenous polar molecules, and phase III processes export these species from cells into bile or urine.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Together, these steps convert lipophilic drugs into more polar metabolites and define overall clearance, bioavailability, and the potential for drug–drug interactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Quantitatively, the smooth endoplasmic reticulum of the liver cell is the principal organ of drug metabolism, although every biological tissue has some ability to metabolize drugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Factors responsible for the liver's contribution to drug metabolism include that it is a large organ, that it is the first organ perfused by chemicals absorbed in the gut, and that there are very high concentrations of most drug-metabolizing enzyme systems relative to other organs.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drugs absorbed in the gastrointestinal tract enters the liver through the hepatic portal system.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The drug is said to show the *first pass effect* if it becomes significantly metabolized before reaching systemic circulation.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Other sites of extrahepatic drug metabolism include epithelial cells of the GI tract, lungs, kidneys, and skin.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] These sites are usually responsible for localized toxicity reactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The duration and intensity of the pharmacological action of many lipophilic drugs are determined by the rate at which they are metabolized to inactive products.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The Cytochrome P450 monooxygenase system (CYP) is particularly important in this process.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In general, factors that increase metabolic activity (enzyme induction) decrease drug exposure, whereas inhibition increases drug concentrations and prolongs drug action.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] However, for prodrugs that require metabolic activation, enzyme induction may increase toxicity rather than reduce it.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Many clinically important drug interactions result from induction or inhibition of drug-metabolizing enzymes.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] For example, the prodrugs cyclophosphamide and ifosfamide are activated primarily by CYP2B6 and CYP3A4 into cytotoxic metabolites such as phosphoramide mustard and chloroacetaldehyde.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Co-administration of strong CYP inducers such as phenytoin or rifampicin can accelerate bioactivation and increase the risk of toxicity, including severe myelosuppression and hemorrhagic cystitis.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug interactions are commonly evaluated relative to theoretical models of noninteraction, including Loewe additivity and Bliss independence.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Interactions may be synergistic, producing greater-than-expected effects or toxicity, or antagonistic, reducing therapeutic efficacy.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Physiological factors affecting drug metabolism include age, sex, diet, enterohepatic circulation, gut microbiota, and inherited genetic variation (pharmacogenetics).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism is generally slower in fetal, neonatal, and elderly individuals than in healthy adults.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Gut microorganisms can alter drug metabolism through chemical modification of drugs, thereby affecting efficacy and toxicity.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] For example, *Eggerthella lenta* can inactivate digoxin.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Genetic polymorphisms in drug-metabolizing enzymes contribute substantially to interindividual variability in drug response.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] One well-known example is the alcohol flush reaction, caused by variants in ALDH2, which reduce aldehyde dehydrogenase activity and impair acetaldehyde metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Polymorphisms in enzymes such as N-acetyltransferase, CYP2D6, CYP3A4, DPYD, and UGT1A1 can alter drug clearance and toxicity risk.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Slow acetylators with reduced NAT2 activity are more susceptible to adverse effects from drugs such as isoniazid, hydralazine, procainamide, and phenelzine.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Genotyping for some drug-metabolizing enzymes is now recommended prior to therapy.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] For example, DPYD testing is used before treatment with 5-fluorouracil or capecitabine, and UGT1A1 testing before irinotecan administration, in order to reduce the risk of severe toxicity.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Expression of drug‑metabolizing enzymes and transporters is dynamically regulated by ligand‑activated xenobiotic‑sensing nuclear receptors, including the pregnane X receptor (PXR), constitutive androstane receptor (CAR), and aryl hydrocarbon receptor (AhR).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The broader roles of these receptors in coordinating xenobiotic defense across different organisms and chemical classes are described in xenobiotic metabolism#Xenobiotic sensing and regulation.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Dose, frequency, route of administration, tissue distribution, and protein binding can also influence drug metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Pathological conditions including liver, kidney, and heart disease may substantially alter drug metabolism and clearance.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism has major clinical implications because it determines drug exposure, therapeutic response, and the risk of adverse effects in individual patients.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Variability in metabolic capacity due to genetic polymorphisms, comorbid disease, age, and drug–drug interactions can lead to underexposure with loss of efficacy or overexposure with toxicity at standard doses.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] For these reasons, characterization of metabolic pathways is an essential component of dose selection, clinical trial design, and rational management of combination drug therapy.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] First-pass metabolism (first-pass effect) refers to presystemic biotransformation, primarily in the gut wall and liver, that occurs after oral administration and reduces the fraction of active drug reaching the systemic circulation.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The extent of first-pass metabolism influences oral bioavailability and may necessitate higher oral doses, alternative routes of administration, or specific formulation strategies.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] A prodrug is a pharmacologically inactive or less active compound that is designed to undergo enzymatic or chemical conversion in the body to release an active drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Prodrug strategies exploit predictable metabolic pathways, including first-pass metabolism, to improve oral bioavailability, solubility, tissue targeting, or tolerability of therapeutic agents.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Active metabolites are biotransformation products that retain pharmacological activity and can contribute substantially to both therapeutic and adverse effects of a parent drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Recognition of clinically important active metabolites is critical for interpreting dose–response relationships, understanding prolonged or delayed effects, and anticipating toxicity in patients with impaired clearance or altered metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism can decrease toxicity through detoxification of xenobiotics but can also generate reactive or toxic metabolites that cause organ injury.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Bioactivation to reactive intermediates, often mediated by cytochrome P450 enzymes, is an important mechanism underlying dose‑related and idiosyncratic hepatotoxicity, hypersensitivity reactions, and other forms of drug‑induced tissue damage.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The therapeutic index (TI) is commonly defined as the ratio of the median toxic dose (TD50) to the median effective dose (ED50).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Metabolic clearance is a key determinant of the therapeutic index because it influences systemic exposure to parent drug and metabolites at a given dose.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Alterations in drug metabolism caused by enzyme induction, enzyme inhibition, or genetic variation can therefore significantly change the therapeutic index of a drug, particularly for drugs with narrow safety margins.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Reduced metabolism may increase drug concentrations and toxicity, whereas accelerated metabolism may reduce efficacy.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Interindividual differences and drug–drug interactions that alter metabolic clearance can narrow or widen a drug’s effective and safe concentration range, sometimes necessitating dose adjustment or therapeutic drug monitoring for medicines with a narrow therapeutic index.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Variability in drug‑metabolizing enzymes provides a major rationale for personalized medicine approaches such as pharmacogenetic testing and individualized dosing regimes.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Genotype‑guided selection and dosing of drugs metabolized by polymorphic enzymes, for example CYP2D6, CYP2C19 or thiopurine S‑methyltransferase, can improve efficacy and reduce the risk of serious adverse drug reactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Multidrug resistance is the ability of tumour cells, microorganisms, or other pathological cells to resist the effects of multiple structurally and functionally distinct drugs, often through mechanisms that reduce intracellular concentrations of active drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Altered expression or function of drug-metabolizing enzymes and associated transporters can contribute to multidrug resistance by lowering intracellular concentrations of active drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In oncology and infectious diseases, induction of metabolic pathways or efflux transporters in tumour or microbial cells, as well as host variability in drug metabolism, can reduce exposure to active drug and compromise treatment outcomes.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The following examples illustrate how differences in drug-metabolizing enzymes and transport pathways translate into clinically important variability in efficacy, toxicity, and drug–drug interactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] They highlight common mechanisms, including prodrug activation, enzyme inhibition or induction, and formation of reactive metabolites, and show how these mechanisms guide prescribing decisions, drug monitoring, and guideline recommendations.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Clopidogrel is a thienopyridine antiplatelet prodrug that requires oxidative bioactivation by hepatic cytochrome P450 enzymes, particularly CYP2C19, to form an active thiol metabolite that irreversibly inhibits the P2Y12 receptor on platelets.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Reduced CYP2C19 function, due to loss-of-function genetic polymorphisms or concomitant use of CYP2C19 inhibitors, decreases the formation of the active metabolite and attenuates the antiplatelet effect.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Such variability in clopidogrel metabolism has been associated with increased rates of thrombotic events, particularly stent thrombosis and myocardial infarction, and has prompted consideration of alternative P2Y12 inhibitors or genotype-guided therapy in some clinical settings.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Codeine is a prodrug that requires O-demethylation by cytochrome P450 2D6 (CYP2D6) to form morphine, which contributes substantially to its analgesic effect.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Individuals who are CYP2D6 poor metabolizers may obtain little or no analgesia from standard codeine doses, whereas ultrarapid metabolizers can produce higher morphine concentrations and are at increased risk of opioid toxicity, including serious respiratory depression.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Concerns about variable metabolism and reports of fatal toxicity in children, particularly in CYP2D6 fast metabolizers, have led regulatory agencies and professional societies to recommend limiting or avoiding the use of codeine in paediatric patients and to favor alternative analgesic strategies.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Grapefruit juice contains furanocoumarins and related compounds that inhibit cytochrome P450 3A4 (CYP3A4) in the intestinal wall, leading to reduced first-pass metabolism of susceptible drugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] For oral medications that undergo extensive intestinal CYP3A4-mediated presystemic metabolism, co-administration with grapefruit juice can markedly increase systemic exposure and thereby heighten the risk of concentration-dependent adverse effects.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] This interaction illustrates the clinical importance of enzyme inhibition and first-pass metabolism in determining the bioavailability and safety of many drugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Rifampicin is a rifamycin antibiotic that acts as a potent inducer of several drug-metabolizing enzymes and transporters, including cytochrome P450 3A4 (CYP3A4) and P-glycoprotein, predominantly through activation of the pregnane X receptor (PXR).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Induction by rifampicin can increase the clearance and reduce the plasma concentrations of many co-administered drugs, including oral contraceptives, anticoagulants, and certain antiretroviral agents, and has been associated with loss of efficacy and therapeutic failure.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] This interaction illustrates the clinical relevance of enzyme and transporter induction in altering drug exposure and may necessitate dose adjustment or the selection of alternative therapy.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] At therapeutic doses, acetaminophen (paracetamol) is primarily cleared by hepatic conjugation pathways, including glucuronidation and sulfation, which produce non-toxic, water-soluble metabolites.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] A small fraction is oxidized by cytochrome P450 enzymes, particularly CYP2E1, to form N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine (NAPQI), a highly reactive intermediate that is normally detoxified by conjugation with glutathione.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] In overdose or in conditions that deplete glutathione, the accumulation of NAPQI leads to covalent binding to cellular proteins, mitochondrial oxidative stress, and centrilobular hepatocellular injury that can progress to acute liver failure.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] This example illustrates how reactive metabolites generated during drug metabolism can be central mediators of toxicity.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The integration of drug metabolism data with pharmacokinetic principles enables quantitative prediction of systemic drug exposure and supports clinical dose optimization across diverse patient populations.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism is a primary determinant of systemic drug exposure, quantified through pharmacokinetic parameters including area-under-the-curve (AUC), clearance, and elimination half-life.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The hepatic extraction ratio (EH) describes the fraction of drug irreversibly removed during a single pass through the liver and ranges from 0 (no extraction) to 1 (complete extraction).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] This ratio is determined by the relationship between intrinsic clearance (CLint, the liver's enzymatic capacity to metabolize drug) and hepatic blood flow (QH, approximately 90 L/hour in humans).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The hepatic extraction ratio can be defined experimentally as: $E_{H}={\frac {C_{in}-C_{out}}{C_{in}}}$ where $E_{H}$ is the hepatic extraction ratio, $C_{in}$ is the drug concentration entering the liver, and $C_{out}$ is the drug concentration leaving the liver.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] For drugs with high extraction ratios (EH > 0.7), hepatic clearance becomes blood flow-limited and largely independent of enzyme activity or protein binding; conversely, drugs with low extraction ratios (EH < 0.3) exhibit clearance limited by intrinsic metabolic capacity rather than perfusion.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] This distinction has critical implications for first-pass metabolism following oral administration, where hepatic bioavailability may be approximated as 1 − EH for drugs that are completely absorbed and undergo negligible intestinal first-pass metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] By incorporating tissue-specific expression of drug-metabolizing enzymes (cytochrome P450s, conjugating enzymes) and transporter proteins, PBPK models simulate how metabolic pathways influence systemic exposure, tissue distribution, and elimination across different patient populations.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] These models enable prediction of untested clinical scenarios including metabolism-mediated drug-drug interactions, effects of hepatic impairment on metabolic clearance, and age-related changes in enzyme activity affecting pediatric dosing without conducting dedicated clinical trials.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] where $V_{T}$ is tissue volume, $C_{T}$ is tissue drug concentration, $Q_{T}$ is tissue blood flow, $C_{A}$ is arterial drug concentration, and $C_{V,T}$ is venous drug concentration exiting the tissue.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] $CL_{int,H}$ is whole-liver intrinsic clearance, $CL_{int,in\ vitro}$ is intrinsic clearance measured in vitro, $MPPGL$ is microsomal protein per gram liver, and $LW$ is liver weight.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] $CL_{H}$ is hepatic clearance, $Q_{H}$ is hepatic blood flow, $f_{u}$ is the unbound fraction of drug in blood, and $CL_{int,H}$ is whole-liver intrinsic clearance.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] PBPK models incorporating drug metabolism parameters are increasingly accepted by regulatory agencies including the FDA for supporting clinical pharmacology decisions, justifying clinical study designs, and waiving studies in special populations when adequately validated.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] The FDA issued guidance in September 2018 outlining format and content expectations for PBPK analyses submitted to support drug applications.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism emerged from broader nineteenth- and early twentieth-century investigations into the biotransformation and detoxification of foreign compounds, including medicinal agents, aromatic compounds, and other xenobiotics (see Xenobiotic metabolism § History).
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Early work demonstrated that administered drugs could undergo chemical transformation in the body through reactions such as oxidation and amino acid conjugation, altering pharmacological activity and facilitating elimination.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] By the early twentieth century, additional pathways including oxidation–reduction, methylation, acetylation, and sulfonation had been recognized in the metabolism of therapeutic agents.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Drug metabolism became a distinct discipline during the mid-twentieth century alongside the development of modern pharmacology and pharmacokinetics.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Richard Tecwyn Williams helped formalize the conceptual framework for metabolic biotransformation by classifying reactions into phase I and phase II processes in his 1947 monograph *Detoxication Mechanisms*.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Subsequent research identified microsomal cytochrome P450 enzymes as the principal catalysts of phase I drug oxidation and glutathione S-transferases as major phase II enzymes.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] These discoveries established the biochemical basis of drug clearance, drug interactions, metabolic bioactivation, and interindividual variability in therapeutic response.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Since the late twentieth century, drug metabolism research has advanced through improved characterization of enzyme systems and regulatory mechanisms, with particular emphasis on interindividual variability and prediction of human clearance.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Major developments included quantitative proteomic methods for measuring enzyme abundance in human tissues, enabling more accurate physiologically-based pharmacokinetic modeling and *in vitro*-*in vivo* extrapolation of clearance predictions.
[src:drug-metabolism/drug-metabolism] Non-cytochrome P450 enzymes including UDP-glucuronosyltransferases, aldehyde oxidase, and carboxylesterases received increased attention as significant contributors to drug clearance, though predicting their *in vivo* activity from *in vitro* systems remains challenging.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] If the molecule induces enzymes that are responsible for its own metabolism, this is called **auto-induction** (or **auto-inhibition** if there is inhibition).
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] These processes are particular forms of gene expression regulation.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] These terms are of particular interest to pharmacology, and more specifically to drug metabolism and drug interactions.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] In the late 1950s and early 1960s, the French molecular biologists François Jacob and Jacques Monod became the first to explain enzyme induction, in the context of the lac operon of Escherichia coli.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] In the absence of lactose, the constitutively expressed lac repressor protein binds to the operator region of the DNA and prevents the transcription of the operon genes.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] When present, lactose binds to the lac repressor, causing it to separate from the DNA and thereby enabling transcription to occur.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] Monod and Jacob generated this theory following 15 years of work by them and others (including Joshua Lederberg), partially as an explanation for Monod's observation of diauxie.
[src:drug-metabolism/enzyme-induction-and-inhibition] Strong, moderate, and weak inducers are drugs that decreases the AUC of sensitive index substrates of a given metabolic pathway by ≥80%, ≥50% to <80%, and ≥20% to <50%, respectively.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] The effect is most associated with orally administered medications, but some drugs still undergo first-pass metabolism even when delivered via an alternate route (e.g., IV, IM, etc.).
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] During this metabolism, drug is lost during the process of absorption which is generally related to the liver and gut wall.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] The liver is the major site of first pass effect; however, it can also occur in the lungs, vasculature or other metabolically active tissues in the body.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Notable drugs that experience a significant first pass effect are buprenorphine, chlorpromazine, cimetidine, diazepam, ethanol (drinking alcohol), imipramine, insulin, lidocaine, midazolam, morphine, pethidine, propranolol, and tetrahydrocannabinol (THC).
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] First-pass metabolism is not to be confused with phase I metabolism, which is a separate process.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] First-pass metabolism may occur in the liver (for propranolol, lidocaine, clomethiazole, and nitroglycerin) or in the gut (for benzylpenicillin and insulin).
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] The four primary systems that affect the first pass effect of a drug are the enzymes of the gastrointestinal lumen, gastrointestinal wall enzymes, bacterial enzymes and hepatic enzymes.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] After a water-soluble drug is swallowed, it is absorbed by the digestive system and enters the hepatic portal system.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] It is carried through the portal vein into the liver before it reaches the rest of the body.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] The liver metabolizes many drugs, sometimes to such an extent that only a small amount of active drug emerges from the liver to the rest of the circulatory system.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] This *first pass* through the liver thus may greatly reduce the bioavailability of the drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] An example of a drug where first-pass metabolism is a complication and disadvantage is in the antiviral drug remdesivir.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Remdesivir cannot be administered orally because the entire dose would be trapped in the liver with little achieving systemic circulation or reaching target organs and cells (for example, cells infected with SARS-CoV-2).
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] For this reason, remdesivir is administered by IV infusion, bypassing the portal vein.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] However, significant hepatic extraction still occurs because of second pass metabolism, whereby a fraction of venous blood travels through the hepatic portal vein and hepatocytes.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] In drug design, drug candidates may have good druglikeness but fail on first-pass metabolism because it is biochemically selective.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Physiologically based pharmacokinetic models (PBPK) are used to predict first-pass metabolism, although they require compound-specific adjustments due to variability in intestinal mucosal permeability and other factors.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Enzyme expression also varies between individuals, which may influence the efficiency of first-pass metabolism and thus the bioavailability of the drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Cytochromes P450, especially CYP3A4, play a crucial role in first-pass metabolism, affecting the bioavailability of drugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Converting a drug into a prodrug can help avoid first-pass metabolism, thereby improving its bioavailability.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] In *in vitro* models, such as the use of microfluidic chips that simulate the gut and liver, allow first-pass metabolism to be studied more accurately, facilitating the development of drugs with better absorption profiles.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Alternative routes of administration, such as insufflation, rectal administration, intravenous, intramuscular, inhalational aerosol, transdermal, or sublingual, avoid or partially avoid the first pass effect because they allow drugs to be absorbed directly into the systemic circulation.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Drugs with high first pass effect typically have a considerably higher oral dose than sublingual or parenteral dose.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] There is marked individual variation in the oral dose due to differences in the extent of first-pass metabolism, frequently among several other factors.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Oral bioavailability of many vulnerable drugs appears to be increased in patients with compromised liver function.
[src:drug-metabolism/first-pass-metabolism] Bioavailability is also increased if another drug competing for first-pass metabolism enzymes is given concurrently (e.g., propranolol and chlorpromazine).
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Glucuronidation consists of transfer of the glucuronic acid component of uridine diphosphate glucuronic acid to a substrate by any of several types of UDP-glucuronosyltransferase.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] UDP-glucuronic acid (glucuronic acid linked via a glycosidic bond to uridine diphosphate) is an intermediate in the process and is formed in the liver.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] One example is the N-glucuronidation of an aromatic amine, 4-aminobiphenyl, by UGT1A4 or UGT1A9 from human, rat, or mouse liver.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] The substances resulting from glucuronidation are known as glucuronides (or glucuronosides) and are typically much more water-soluble than the non-glucuronic acid-containing substances from which they were originally synthesised.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] The human body uses glucuronidation to make a large variety of substances more water-soluble, and, in this way, allow for their subsequent elimination from the body through urine or feces (via bile from the liver).
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Hormones are glucuronidated to allow for easier transport around the body.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Pharmacologists have linked drugs to glucuronic acid to allow for more effective delivery of a broad range of potential therapeutics.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Sometimes toxic substances are also less toxic after glucuronidation.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] The conjugation of xenobiotic molecules with hydrophilic molecular species such as glucuronic acid is known as phase II metabolism.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Glucuronidation occurs mainly in the liver, although the enzyme responsible for its catalysis, UDP-glucuronyltransferase, has been found in all major body organs (e.g., intestine, kidneys, brain, adrenal gland, spleen, and thymus).
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Various factors affect the rate of glucuronidation, which in turn will affect these molecules' clearance from the body.
[src:drug-metabolism/glucuronidation] Generally, an increased rate of glucuronidation results in a loss of potency for the target drugs or compounds.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] A **prodrug** is a pharmacologically inactive medication or compound that, after intake, is metabolized (i.e., converted within the body) into a pharmacologically active drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Instead of administering a drug directly, a corresponding prodrug can be used to improve how the drug is absorbed, distributed, metabolized, and excreted (ADME).
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Prodrugs are often designed to improve bioavailability when a drug itself is poorly absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] A prodrug may be used to improve how selectively the drug interacts with cells or processes that are not its intended target.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] This reduces adverse or unintended effects of a drug, especially important in treatments like chemotherapy, which can have severe unintended and undesirable side effects.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Many herbal extracts historically used in medicine contain glycosides (sugar derivatives) of the active agent, which are hydrolyzed in the intestines to release the active and more bioavailable aglycone.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] For example, salicin is a β-D-glucopyranoside that is cleaved by esterases to release salicylic acid.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), first made by Felix Hoffmann at Bayer in 1897, is a synthetic prodrug of salicylic acid.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] However, in other cases, such as codeine and morphine, the administered drug is enzymatically activated to form sugar derivatives (morphine-glucuronides) that are more active than the parent compound.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] The first synthetic antimicrobial drug, arsphenamine, discovered in 1909 by Sahachiro Hata in the laboratory of Paul Ehrlich, is not toxic to bacteria until it has been converted to an active form by the body.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Likewise, prontosil, the first sulfa drug (discovered by Gerhard Domagk in 1932), must be cleaved in the body to release the active molecule, sulfanilamide.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Since that time, many other examples have been identified.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Terfenadine, the first non-sedating antihistamine, had to be withdrawn from the market because of the small risk of a serious side effect.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] However, terfenadine was discovered to be the prodrug of the active molecule, fexofenadine, which does not carry the same risks as the parent compound.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Therefore, fexofenadine could be placed on the market as a safe replacement for the original drug.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Loratadine, another non-sedating antihistamine, is the prodrug of desloratadine, which is largely responsible for the antihistaminergic effects of the parent compound.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] However, in this case the parent compound does not have the side effects associated with terfenadine, and so both loratadine and its active metabolite, desloratadine, are currently marketed.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Approximately 10% of all marketed drugs worldwide can be considered prodrugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Since 2008, at least 30 prodrugs have been approved by the FDA.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Seven prodrugs were approved in 2015 and six in 2017.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Both major types can be further categorized into subtypes, based on factors such as (Type I) whether the intracellular bioactivation location is also the site of therapeutic action, or (Type 2) whether or not bioactivation occurs in the gastrointestinal fluids or in the circulation system.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Type IA prodrugs include many antimicrobial and chemotherapy agents (e.g., 5-flurouracil).
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Type IB agents rely on metabolic enzymes, especially in hepatic cells, to bioactivate the prodrugs intracellularly to active drugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Importantly, prodrugs can belong to multiple subtypes (i.e., Mixed-Type).
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] A Mixed-Type prodrug is one that is bioactivated at multiple sites, either in parallel or sequential steps.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] For example, a prodrug, which is bioactivated concurrently in both target cells and metabolic tissues, could be designated as a "Type IA/IB" prodrug (e.g., HMG Co-A reductase inhibitors and some chemotherapy agents; note the symbol " / " applied here).
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] When a prodrug is bioactivated sequentially, for example initially in GI fluids then systemically within the target cells, it is designated as a "Type IIA-IA" prodrug (e.g., tenofovir disoproxil; note the symbol " - " applied here).
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] Many antibody- virus- and gene-directed enzyme prodrug therapies (ADEPTs, VDEPTs, GDEPTs) and proposed nanoparticle- or nanocarrier-linked drugs can understandably be Sequential Mixed-Type prodrugs.
[src:drug-metabolism/prodrug] To differentiate these two Subtypes, the symbol dash " - " is used to designate and to indicate sequential steps of bioactivation, and is meant to distinguish from the symbol slash " / " used for the Parallel Mixed-Type prodrugs.
